social_posts.post_text: Last time we spoke to each other was this past Friday, obviously about kicks. One of our shared passions. Another shared passion was Hip hop. Certain aspects of what we both loved didn’t even need to be talked about, we knew our motives and reasons. A total understanding of what we both stood for, believed in and foremost, loved about the cultures we grew up in. We had much in common. Love for our family, a good laugh and love for life in general. Life feels very unfair when a loving person takes their last breath way too soon. I still can’t believe you’re gone. We always joked brother from another but that’s exactly how it feels right now. You were a good person. I won’t forget you Sukhi ❤️
Remember that old photo of CL Smooth wearing the OG Resin’s and Pete Rock on the Marina BW’s? I keep my past around. One of my favorite bring backs this year. The OG Resin.

Favorite Nocta product till date. Leather quality reminds of the 2017 Rocafella AF-1. It’s really nice. Drake details throughout the product for that special Drizzy touch. The AIR branding on the medial side of the midsole feels kinda off imo. Love the heart detail on the outsole and of course the “Love you Forever” on the midsole. If you don’t like Drake to begin with, you probably won’t like this shoe. But if you do like the artist and the AF-1 silhouette, you’re definitely in for a treat.
A nod to the earliest days of AF-1. This colorway should be no stranger to a true fan. Another one from the COTM series. I’m trigger-happy with all of ‘em. Can’t deny and don’t want to. Love ‘em.

It was the now creative director of New Balance’s Made in USA division, Teddy Santis, who leaked a photo of the new 990v6 on Instagram in the early Summer of 2021. Finally, after 1,5 years of waiting,  we’re only several days away of the official EU launch date of NB’s next chapter in their iconic 990 series. The Version 6 arrives in the New England brand’s signature grey colorway. A mesh base with leather and suede paneling gives the familiar design a new twist. For the first time, the “N” logo on the quarter panel does not sit atop a suede panel, but rather on the perforated leather webbing that runs across the mesh base. More mesh is visible than on past iterations, giving the silhouette a sleeker, streamlined look. The heel overlays have been reworked too, as has the entire sole unit. As previous versions the ENCAP cushioning technology returns on the V6. I like the V6. Despite the chunky midsole the feel on feet is surprisingly light. Quality of the materials and the overall build are in line with the expectations of a Made in the USA release. I would recommend a TTS fit. The 990V6 drops in full family sizing this Thursday the 15th of December. Big up to @newbalance for sending over an early pair.

For some reason I’ve bought almost every (good) white AF-1 this year (some even double or triple). My apologies for the lack of diversity but how can you stop crack from being crack. I hope you get my point.

Thx for the invite @oqium 🍹
New store opens tomorrow. They got some heat tucked away.

Patent leather AF1s are a guilty pleasure of mine, wild color blocking, if done right, only adds to the pleasure. Nike remains to be the true king of patent leather sneakers, ever since they introduced it on the Jordan XI back in 1996. These two colorways are my unmistakable favorites from the recent Undefeated x Nike AF1 quartet. One of them (right) obviously linking back to their 2005 Clerks Pack release, where we saw the same colorway on the Dunk NL. For some reason the patent leather used on these AF1s feels a bit thicker and more flexible. Hopefully resulting in less creasing. Overall build, quality, details and the special box are really nice. I’m a bit surprised that the EU releases were priced much lower as the first two exclusive Undefeated colorways. €129 feels very reasonable for this type of shoe and packaging. These two rank pretty high on my year-end list. Shout out to the ❤️🔌 for these.
Way better in hand than expected. You can't deny the 'Monarch' Patta Wave resemblance. The average Air Max 1 enthusiast will definitely enjoy these. Quality and overall build is solid on this pair.

My Top 3 favorite Nike releases of 2022. Will be sharing a general Top 10 in the upcoming days. Lucky enough to have doubles and even triples of these three. Couldn’t think of any other Nike releases that top these three in ranking. Would be interesting to see your Top 3 Nike releases of 2022. If you want to share yours, please drop them down below.

The 21 year old 'Ugly Duckling' Dunk pack somewhat brought back on a set of Air Max 1s. This Honeydew colorway makes a clear reference to the 'Ceramic' colorway of the original Dunk trilogy in terms of color inspiration, even though the shades are a tad bit off. The upper comes in the signature OG 'Ugly Duckling' suede construction. The soft suede actually feels much nicer than expected. The embroided duck on the heel feels forced and unnecessary. I would’ve preferred the OG Nike Air branding on the heel and would’ve also moved the duck to the insole. Overall build and quality of this pair is good. I also like the 'Pecan' colorway of this set. Which strangely enough seems to make no reference to the OG pack (or other Dunks from that timeframe), as I can’t find any link color wise, besides the signature Co.JP suede build in that typical color blocking. Overall the pack feels a bit disappointing, especially when the inspiration is as colorful and iconic as the original 'Ugly Duckling' pack. That significant era of Dunks definitely deserved a little bit more representation here.

As promised my Top 10 favorite releases of 2022, in no particular order. In general as a brand, Nike took the cake this year and New Balance finished in the runner-up position. I also really liked what Asics brought to the table this year, caught me a couple of them “Tigers”. In terms of best model of 2022, the AF1 wins that title for me this year, closely followed by the 990V3. It was a solid year in terms of releases. A bit much to be honest. Together with @morprime I created the new Omniracer model (Saffron & Meranti) for @kangaroossneakers. Again, such an amazing opportunity and experience. More Triggah stuff is coming in 2023, as I’m in the final stages of finishing several projects for 2023. Stay tuned.

- Nike Air Max 1 Patta Wave (Platinum White)
- Nike Air Jordan 1 Lost & Found 
- New Balance 990 V3 JJJJound
- New Balance 990 V3 Marblehead
- Nike Air Jordan 3 Firered
- Nike Air Huarache OG Resin
- Nike Air Force 1 Color of the Month White
- New Balance 990 V4 Kith United Arrows & Sons 
- Nike Air Force 1 Undefeated “Clerks” 
- Asics Gel lyte III x SF x Atmos “Alley Cats”
Still stuck in my ways. Best wishes ❤️ for you and yours.

Here we have the other half of the 'Ugly Duckling' Pack inspired Air Max 1 set, which I partially reviewed when I shared my thoughts on the Honeydew colorway last week (just go back on my feed). Now most of last weeks conclusion also counts for the 'Pecan’ counterpart of this set. Only conclusion I want to add is the in hand look and feel of the 'Pecan' colorway and I must admit I’m pretty impressed. A really nice Fall themed colorway sits on a soft suede upper and the only thing that’s contrasting on this earthy palette is the sparkling white midsole. The build on this particular pair is pristine. A perfect pair for Fall and definitely my favorite of the set. Big up to my good friends over at @footshop for sending over a pair.
Are these the best Air Max 1 releases from 2022? Let’s talk.
Croc & Python. Choose your predator, 🐊 or 🐍?

Stupid fresh updated versions of the OG ‘86 Rivalry Low. Both colorways fall under the so called “Can’t go wrong” category. That OG Ewing inspired logo remains to be one of my favorite adidas logo’s. A very nice retro with several details (hangtag & tissue paper) that nod to the late Eighties. This is the good stuff y’all. Lastly, leather upper feels very premium.
Found while cleaning. Apologies are in order. Where do these rank on the Air Jordan IV ladder?
The trigger had to be pulled. Pictures don’t do justice. I’m happy with my choice of going TTS.
So 'Big Bubble' Air 180’s are coming in 2024. Let’s speculate! What are we hoping for?

Nike is looking back to the last occurrence of the 'Rabbit' zodiac animal for some inspiration on this all new Dunk Low version. That would be in 2011, when Nike dropped one of the best 'Year Of The Rabbit’ releases in history (pop quiz on my stories). For 2023, Nike is transmitting the same colorway and added some details to the Dunk Low silhouette. Inspired by a traditional milk cream-flavored candy popular in China. I forgot the name of the candy, drop it below if you know. The outsole calls out the connection to the …… as the left sole states 2011 while the opposite shoe displays 2023. Materials used on this Dunk feel very mediocre, instead of premium as the box label clearly states. A bit disappointing. Overall a very nice packaged release with loads of details nodding to the previous (and better) release of 2011.
Leftover shot from last year when I visited @wimwam.1969 to check his collection. Holding a Nike Bespoke Air Max 1 in a subtle grey colorway.
Appreciation post. House of Pain x Adidas Originals Campus 80’s from 2009. Never worn. A true gem in my collection. Limited to only 1500 pairs worldwide.

I noticed that it’s been almost five years since this shoe came out. Remember the sizing problem on these? The shoe fits a good half size bigger. That info wasn’t shared at first, causing “serious” problems for the people that were able to grab and were planning to wear their pairs. I’m also still surprised that Nike didn’t go ham on this new hybrid model after the initial Wotherspoon release. Only a handful GR versions made it on to the shelves a couple of years ago. It’s a really strong fusion, the Air Max 97 and the Air Max 1. The Tinker Tresser.

2015 was such a strong year. A broad variety of memorable releases came to be that year. Personally I really enjoyed the 25th anniversary releases of the Asics Gel Lyte III model, delivered by numerous established sneaker boutiques. One of those commemorative releases was this 'Boston Tea Party' (The Boston Tea Party was an American political and mercantile protest by the Sons of Liberty in Boston) themed Gel Lyte III by Boston based boutique @cncpts. A true powerhouse when it comes to sneaker collaborations. This particular pair always reminds me of that time when boutique collaborations had a higher profile in the community. Times change but luckily we still have the pairs that tell the story.

2001 was a great year for Nike Air Force 1 aficionados. Some of the best Air Force 1s released in that year. Hong Kong’s, Linen’s, Cocoa Snake and Taiwan’s, were all rolled out that year. Just to name a few of those classics. Japan-based atmos has been playing a major role in the industry for decades with ongoing sneaker collaborations with various brands as well as retail spaces all over the world, but it might’ve started all with this subtle Air Force 1 Low colorway from 2001. The classic Atmos x Nike Air Force 1. Easily in my Top 5 best Air Force 1s ever. It’s about as basic as an Air Force 1 Low can get, a two-toned colorway in a Navy/Grey ‘Georgetown’ colorway, but it works so well. Simplicity at it’s finest. Certified.
The Source Magazine Tech-Gear Profile 'Project Chill' Style Editorial from the November 1997 Issue. Photography By @jonathanmannion
Let’s go back to 1992.

Bought me some Bape’s when the news came out. There is no coincidence I bought this colorway because it resembles the 2001 classic 'Cocoa Snake' colorway on the Air Force 1. That’s the reason why I bought it. That’s the irony. Bape getting a “pass” for so long and being a household name in our industry made it feel a bit weird to me, last weeks news. But I guess if they’re going after one, they have to knock on every door. Any thoughts on the matter?

A very special thanks to @hanonshop (& @thomaslindie) for sending over an early pair of their upcoming collaboration with Mizuno on the Contender Runner. The basis for their interpretation of Mizuno’s 90’s running classic, the Contender, is the grampus dolphin. Check a more in depth backstory on HANON’s website. This collaboration will first release at HANON at the 3rd of February, followed by a wider release on the 11th of February.
Let’s go back to 1993.
@heineken 👀
If you like unexpected conversations, this is your shoe to wear. It’s a wild one, just like it’s predecessor, the original Air Max 1 Atmos Animal. What’s the better version? 2006 or 2017.
Lets go back to 2003. Nike Air Huarache Bisque. Fresh in the box.
Let’s go back to 1991. Nike Air Pegasus 'Cherry'.

2023 marks the 30th anniversary of the 'Made in USA' New Balance 998 model. Expecting some new retro’s from Teddy Santis and his team, this year, isn’t a strange thought. Maybe we will get some new Kith versions or something exquisite from Boston’s own Concepts. Both brands have a solid reputation when it comes down to NB collaborations. JJJJound maybe? Aimé Leon Dore perhaps? All possible. Whatever is coming for the 998 silhouette, I’m here for it. If anything is actually coming. Either way, it’s safe to say that after thirty years the 998 is still one of New Balance's flagship models. Let’s hope for something (really) good.

Let’s go back to 2002. 
Nike Air Force 1 High 20th anniversary edition.

So simple but so good. With or without the JJJJound branding. Same formula as the gorgeous green 990V3 from last year. With that really nice contrasting off-white midsole and those matching laces. Build and quality is up to par. Thanks ❤️ @newbalance for the early pair.

Beautiful shoe, the Asics Gel Lyte III 'Super Orange' in the Remastered build, meaning back to the old shape. The design returns to the exact proportions featured in the first pair that @ronniefieg introduced in 2007 when he began his partnership with Asics. Subtle shifts within each area of the shoe deliver an updated silhouette. The premium cut on this shoe strikes at first glance. Less is really more. Subtle base colors with a contrasting orange pop. But the real standout features on this shoe are the details. The remastered build and shape, the premium quality of the material and the overall branding and packaging. This is right up my alley.

Some extra shots of the “Juh-juh-juh-jound” x New Balance 991 in all it’s earth-toned glory. Lovin’ the sandy look/effect when the sunlight hits the grey & brown upper. Peep the Reel I shared yesterday.

The foundation of my love for footwear lies in a feeling. There’s not much I can explain about it. Something sparks at a young age and you either get hooked on something or you don’t. It just hits harder when you’re younger. First love always cuts the deepest. Nothing was readily available when I was younger. Depending on whatever you’re parents would buy for you, at an incomparable frequency to what we’re buying nowadays. Of course with being in charge of your own money. Our urge to go after the unattainable is in our DNA. It drives your determination. It creates passion. It becomes a part of who we are. I can talk endlessly about sneakers, still. For the first twenty years of my life, I did not have much appreciation either for personal memory or for history. Later on I rescued most of those early memories and really valued them. Old friends, high school, family, different era’s of music and so on. A returning aspect in all those memories are sneakers. I always find a link between certain OG silhouettes and memories, or a certain state of mind from a specific moment in past times. Recalling past moments is something we do regularly. The good old days as we like to call ‘em. The pleasure of reminiscing about our past is the joy of finding ourselves again. My passion endures because of that. Let’s go back to 1990 and look at me (last slide) wearing one of my most cherished pairs ever, the Nike Air Tech Challenge 3 ‘Hot Lime'. At the time one of the signature shoes of tennis legend Andre Agassi as part of his (still amazing) Nike Challenge Court collection. I happen to come across a DS and unworn pair very recently. I just had to buy it. Like so many times before, for old times ❤️sake. *Thanks 😎 @milansimons & @mart1nstagram

One of the more notable colorways to ever grace the Nike Air Trainer 1 model is without a doubt the 'Shima Shima'. Originally released in 2003 alongside another Air Trainer 1 and both as part of the 'Shima Shima' pack, which also included three Dunk High colorways and two Air Max 1 colorways. Each model set of ‘Shima’ releases were released simultaneously, but what tied all three capsules together was the unique pinstriping on the interior lining of the shoe. Originally made exclusively for the European, Canadian, and Asian market if I recall correctly. It’s been twenty years after the initial drop, so it’s only right they’ve brought it back. The outcome is a worthy retro, delivered in the signature OG inspired box, with build and quality up to par. An extra set of red laces comes in the box. The newer (2022/2023) retro’s of the Air Trainer 1 fit true to size. No more going up a full size because of the strap pinches your small toe. Those days are over.
Hip hop’s flag at half-mast today. Rest easy Dave 🕊️🤍 De La lost a part of their Soul.
As the Nike ad in 1990 once said: “Hit the ball as loud as you can.” Check the pinned post on my feed for more context on this OG classic.

Couldn’t resist with these 'Lucky Green' AJII’s. Really nice placement of colors with that off-white finish on the midsole, delivering that vintage vibe. Material and build is up to par. I would say the best recent AJII release together with the OG Chicago II’s.

Had the privilege to get an early look at the upcoming Air Max 1 ‘86 Big Bubble retro release. I like it. But I’m a suckah for obscure retro returns. Be your own judge with the help of this short video.

So this Dunk pretty much released out of the blue (no pun) a while ago and grabbed everybody’s attention. The 'Industrial Blue' Denim Dunk shows noticeable Sashiko (Japanese stitching technique) details on the toebox and heel. I’m not convinced that the upper parts are made out of actual Denim material, feels more like a soft canvas to me, but the Denim vibe is definitely present here. Build and materials are up to par. These feel more special compared to a regular degular Dunk release. Solid.
Recent favorites. Tell me yours.

Was expecting these to sell out due to the slight Supreme Dunk SB resemblance but they (obviously) didn’t. Resellers are only targeting a select few AJ1 Highs these days, because there’s no money to be made on the majority of AJ1 Highs and then there’s also the busy release roster. People are picky💰. Can’t blame ‘em. I on the other hand did scoop these up. I hate/love this shoe. Point-blank. There’s no other explanation. Quality is up to par. Jordan Brand keeps there re-imagined/aged theme going with that sail midsole. I like that. Still sitting on SNKRS, as we “speak”. You got my blessing.
Brown or Green?

Ronnie Fieg’s 100th Asics collaboration is here. As the previous 'Super Orange' colorway, this 'Super Yellow' colorway arrives with a remastered GEL-Lyte III silhouette and also coincide with the opening of a new Kith store (Miami). Continuing the 'Super' sub-lineage using a plain base color contrasted with a vibrant accent. The GLIII has also been completely redesigned to its 2007 specifications, which is when Ronnie first worked on the model. Classic Fieg elements with outstanding quality. Congrats to the designer.
Close to the original ‘86 version and not to be compared with the ‘87 version. It’s a matter of taste. Hate it or love it. Or be wherever you need to be.

Thoughts on the recently released 'Soft Grey' Air Max 1 Crepe? It’s a solid colorway, a bit boring and the build on this particular pair is a bit crooked. Quality of the materials is up to par. These will definitely gain more popularity in the future.

Hopefully there are pairs out there with a better finish. Materials are nice. Nothing to complain there. Same goes for the shape. The signature Safari print goes all the way back to 1987, same as the Air Max 1 model. Seeing both come together always catches my attention, regardless of the end result. Didn’t want to pass up on this one.

I wonder what would’ve happened if they went the opposite route and dropped a blue full suede version. The quality on this particular pair is up to par as the video shows. Also no complaints about the build, finish and shape. Solid.

Got invited to the advanced screening of the new AIR movie yesterday. The Warner Bros./Amazon Studios film takes us back to that period in 1984, when Nike Marketing Executive Sonny Vaccaro took a chance on Jordan who, at the time, had not yet set foot on an NBA court. Make sure to tune in to the @sneakerjagers social channels for some exclusive footage of the event. Thanks for the invite Warner Bros.

For most there couldn’t be a clearer motive. Without being melodramatic, I wanted to give that bar some attention. Because it covers the load so perfectly. And as you all know……bars still matter.

The 'Four Horsemen' Air Force 1’s were originally created as a Player Exclusive (PE) for Lebron James right after he signed with Nike in 2003. The “Four Horsemen” Air Force 1 series reference his inner circle of business partners—Maverick Carter, Rich Paul, and Randy Mims—who collectively (with James) are known as the Four Horsemen. Now it’s back and for everybody to grab! Leather looks and feels amazing. You’re looking at the OG AF-1 cut with the embroided Swoosh under the eyestay. The 'Four Horsemen’ AF-1 arrives in the classic signature black box. I’m pleasantly surprised.

My story with the Air Huarache began back in 1991 when Nike introduced this revolutionary design to the world. The Air Huarache was the brainchild of legendary Nike designer Tinker Hatfield & Tom Hartge, who sought to craft a shoe that would revolutionize the industry. Inspired by the ancient sandals of the Native Americans, Hatfield embarked on a mission to create a shoe that would provide a glove-like fit and exceptional comfort.

For me, the Air Huarache still represents the early days of when my passion for footwear had just sparked. The design and OG colors perfectly capture the 1990s. Also my childhood. It’s also a symbol of individuality, creativity, and it’s also one of the first sneakers that started a deep appreciation within myself for the artistry behind sneaker design. 

I shared more personal thoughts on the Air Huarache silhouette with @allthatkicks, for the 2nd part of 'The Unsung Victory', a fan-made publication that celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Nike Air Huarache. Honored to have a voice in the book. Coming soon.

I am still somewhat surprised that the Air Max 1 ‘Athletic Department’ was announced as a Nike Only release so out of the blue, three days before its release. I had not yet seen the new generation Golf Air Max 1s up close. Gladly surprised, as this is thankfully nowhere near its more technical predecessor. The thick shark-tooth golf outsole has been replaced by a much thinner variant, which from the side does not give away that this is a golf sneaker. The only thing that disappoints me a bit about this '86 version is the narrow air bubble opening. This does look a lot less than the original version and thus also feels a tad off. Of course, there is nothing to complain about the colourway. I myself am a big fan of the Air Max 1 'Mesh' from 1999 and this colourway is of course a bit reminiscent of it. Even though the composition is different. I can't comment further on the comfort as I didn't have time to try them on. Still, with this close up look, I am convinced and strongly tempted to buy a pair in the future, even though I don't play golf. But then again, I don't play basketball either....

Designed with the “sneakerhead” community in mind, the INSIDE JOB v1.5 “QUARTZ” is another meticulous collaboration between MORPRIME Industries™, @tommy_triggah, and @kangaroos.originals.

Couldn't resist the last pair in my size of the Air Jordan 1 'Lucky Green' release. This release pays tribute to Michael Jordan's intense rivalry with the Boston Celtics, a team that caused him some of his most unforgettable defeats on the court. Despite scoring an astonishing career-high of 63 points against them, even the great MJ couldn't get the better of the Celtics.

The 'Lucky Green' colorway takes us back to those historic battles. 

The Air Jordan 1's OG features are reimagined in this edition, so we’re getting the best version of the Air Jordan 1 silhouette. 

Furthermore, this version outshines the 2009 Air Jordan 1 'Celtics' from the DMP pack, capturing the essence of that legendary 63-point clinic MJ put on against Boston back in April 1986, while donning the Air Jordan 1. It's worth noting that the Air Jordan 1 High's appearance in 2009 looked similar to what we nowadays know as the Air Jordan 1 Mid. 

From its solid leather quality and true-to-the-OG build to the iconic OG color-blocking, this release perfectly captures the essence of the legendary Air Jordan 1. Its rich history, inspired by Michael Jordan's battles with the Boston Celtics and his historic 63-point game, adds an extra layer of significance to this shoe. Had to cop.

Today marks the 50th anniversary of a pivotal moment in history. On August 11, 1973, DJ Kool Herc, only 18 years old at the time, organized a "Back To School Jam" in the South Bronx for his sister Cindy. Unknowingly, this event would become the birthplace of hip-hop, a genre that would go on to transform music and culture worldwide. Its cultural influence has touched countless lives, mine included, leaving an enduring impact on identity, expression, and connection. From the streets of the South Bronx to a global phenomenon, hip-hop culture emerged 50 years ago, reshaping music, fashion, art, and social expression. A testament to the power of creativity and resilience, it continues to inspire, empower, and bridge diverse voices worldwide. #HipHopAt50

There’s no honoring 50 years of hip-hop culture without mentioning the PUMA Suede, the quintessential B Boy footwear. The unofficial 'What the Suede' combines OG colorways, a premium cut that's a nod to PUMA's VTG Origins. Uniting pure finesse with timeless style, proving that some styles never go out of fashion. Introducing the adidas The Collective Pack: 'From Court to Concrete.' This collection seamlessly bridges the worlds of sports heritage and street fashion. The Conductor High pays homage to timeless court elegance, embodying the grace and precision of the game. On the other hand, the Rivalry Low redefines casual with a street-smart flair, effortlessly navigating the concrete landscape. More than footwear, this pack is a testament to versatility and attitude, capturing the essence of self-expression in every step.

And what better moment to release this pack than during the 50th anniversary of hip-hop culture? A movement that played a pivotal role in bringing sport shoes to the streets, hip-hop has reshaped not only music but also fashion, influencing generations. The adidas The Collective Pack pays tribute to this cultural phenomenon, fusing sports, style, and music in a celebration of individuality.

Drawing inspiration from the old New York Subway tokens, the gold adidas tokens within the collection are a nod to the city's history. These tokens were more than just tokens; they were a form of payment for subway travel, connecting people to the city's heartbeat and culture. The Subway also served as a playground in the 80s for graffiti artists, contributing to the visual and cultural landscape of the streets. This heritage is encapsulated in the tokens, connecting us to a time when self-expression thrived in the concrete environment.

Crafting this pack as The Collective, a collaboration of creative minds including Sneakerqueen, ErniePunk, Defy. New York, and myself, Tommy Triggah, was truly a dream come true. It adds an extra layer of significance, as we united to pay homage to the cultures that inspire us. From the vibrant and expressive world of hip-hop culture to the intensity of basketball culture and the dynamic realm of pop culture, each element is woven into these designs. This collection stands as a reflection of our shared passions and a representation of the beautiful blend of cultures that shape our lives.

You can own a piece of this collective vision that celebrates the convergence of art, sport, and style.

Both styles are now available.

The iconic Terror Squad Air Force 1 is back in the game, and as a hip-hop fanatic, I couldn’t be more excited. These Air Force 1’s, originally reserved for Fat Joe and his crew back in the early 2000s, arrived officially courtesy of Nike. The ‘Black-Out’ version boasts that timeless black and white aesthetic, complete with the classic OG-inspired box and the embroidered Terror Squad logo’s on the heel. 

But here’s the deal – the leather quality on these Air Force 1s is off the charts. It’s some of the finest leather I’ve ever seen on a pair of Nikes, and it’s as premium as it gets.

For fans like me, this is a must-have addition to the collection. It’s more than just an Air Force 1; it’s a piece of hip-hop history. Don’t lean back on these!

@sneakerqueen reigning supreme in our Collective! Her Friends of Family version of the adidas Conductor from our Court to Concrete collection is pure royalty.

This masterpiece goes beyond the hype, with ‘Don’t Believe The Hype’ hidden on the inside of the right tongue and ‘Vintage vs Retro’ discreetly tucked inside the left, quotes that only resonate with the most dedicated enthusiasts. 

Sneakerqueen’s attention to detail is impeccable, with a luxurious shiny silver grey quilted lining and a matching quilted insole. The small crown and heart emblem adorning the gold lace tips add a touch of royalty to every step.

This colorway takes us on a journey down memory lane, resonating with her iconic adidas collaboration from a decade ago. The choice of exotic materials seamlessly blends the flamboyance of hip-hop culture with the heritage of the court.

But it’s the orange basketball detail on the heel that steals the show, truly an amazing tribute to the game that inspires us all.

The Viotech Air Max 1, originally released in 2002, garnered acclaim for its distinctive color scheme. Despite subsequent releases and retrospectives in later years, none have truly captured the essence of the original 2002 version. Given the iconic status of classics like the Viotech Air Max 1, it raises the question: Do the ones of such magnitude deserve a faithful retro to preserve the essence of the original, or is there value in exploring new interpretations to keep evolving? What are your thoughts on this balance between nostalgia and moving forward?

Marking 35 years of the Nike Air Stab this year, the OG ‘88 runner was a stability and Air cushioning icon. However, in 2008, it took an unexpected turn, reportedly stepping off UK shelves due to societal concerns about knife violence. Although making sporadic appearances afterward, the Air Stab has been absent from recent lineups. The OG ‘Electric Green’ and collaborative releases now stand as cherished relics. The question lingers: Could the Air Stab stage a comeback in the future? Do we need one?

In the fabric of life, we often revisit the vibrant moments of our youth, where emotions ran deep, and experiences shaped us. For me, that rewind button often leads to 1991, the era of Andre Agassi’s Nike Air Tech Challenge 3 ‘Volt.’ Back then, tennis played a secondary role (for me), and the allure of Agassi’s signature Challenge Court collection fascinated me in a simpler time when the industry was emerging.

The industry was different—accessibility was a dream. Fantasies were spun from ads and catalogues; desires tempered by financial constraints. This year, fate smiled, and I had the chance to acquire the 1991 ‘Volt,’ still new and boxed. Yet, owning it can’t fully bridge the gap between reality and memory. You can’t buy into an era; you must have lived it.

So, this purchase isn’t just a shoe; it’s a celebration of a bygone authenticity. The ‘Volt’ symbolizes a time that shaped my cultural appreciation. As 2023 draws to a close, it stands as my favorite pickup this year—a tangible link to the past, encapsulating the essence of a bygone era.
